Thanks for sharing the stackblitz. The use of `ngOnchanges` will trigger only if there is a change in the component. So I noticed two things in stackblitz.

 1. `radio` and `table` components are independent of each other.
 2. `app` component is an intermediator between these two components.

So a change in radio component will not trigger the table component and so the ngOnchanges will not trigger.

So the table component should know that you have made some modifications to the radio component. Here, you can make use of `EventEmitter` and `Subject`.

 1. EmitEvent from radio component to app component(event emitter)
 2. Once the event is emitted, using the `Subject` send an Observable to the table component to sort it.

This is one of the right ways to do it.

**app.component.html**

    &lt;app-radio (event)=&quot;emitEvent($event)&quot;&gt;&lt;/app-radio&gt;
    &lt;app-table [sortTableSubject]=&quot;sortTableSubject.asObservable()&quot;&gt;&lt;/app-table&gt;

**app.component.ts**

    export class AppComponent {
      sortTableSubject: Subject&lt;string&gt; = new Subject&lt;string&gt;();
      emitEvent($event){
        console.log($event);
        this.sortTableSubject.next($event);
      }
    }

**radio.component.ts**

    changeSortBy(val: string, table: TableComponent) {
        this.model = {
          sortBy: val
        }
        this.event.emit(&quot;sortByName&quot;); //emit what type of sorting should be done and capture that in parent component
        //table.ngOnChanges();
      }

**table.component.ts**

    ngOnInit() {
        this.sortTableSubject.subscribe(res =&gt; {
          console.log(res);
          alert(&quot;ngOnChanges: &quot; + this.sortBy); // Capturing the event using subject
          // Do your sorting logc here
          //this.arrangeItems();
        });
      }

